---
import BaseHead from "../components/BaseHead.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import { SITE_DESCRIPTION, SITE_TITLE } from "../consts";
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead title={SITE_TITLE} description={SITE_DESCRIPTION} />
  </head>
  <body>
    <Header />
    <main>
      <h1>🧑‍🚀 Hello — I'm traveling in Japan!</h1>

      <p>
        I'll be in Japan between 17 May 2026 and 11 June 2026. This website is
        my personal travel blog where I'll post experiences, photos, tips, maps,
        and small stories from days on the road — from crowded city mornings to
        quiet countryside evenings.
      </p>

      <h2>Where I'll be</h2>
      <p>
        A rough route: Tokyo → Kanazawa → Shirakawago → Takayama → Kyoto →
        Amanohashidate → Okayama → Iya Valley → Hiroshima → Nagato → Fukuoka →
        Kagoshima → Tokyo. Expect trains, temples, shrines, tea houses, lively
        markets, beaches, gardens, mountains, waterfalls, etc.
      </p>
      <p>
        I’m not wibu though, nor do I consume any Japanese media, so don’t
        expect any anime or manga content.
      </p>

      <h2>What I'll share</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Day-by-day notes: small wins, misadventures, and favorite meals.
        </li>
        <li>
          Photography: street scenes, food close-ups, and landscapes at golden
          hour.
        </li>
        <li>
          Practical tips: rail passes, cash vs card, polite phrases, and packing
          notes.
        </li>
        <li>
          Local flavors: ramen, izakaya hopping, sweets, and regional
          specialties.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Quick travel tips</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Carry a charged battery pack — trains and wandering will drain your
          phone.
        </li>
        <li>
          Buy an IC card (Suica/Pasmo) for easy travel on most trains and buses.
        </li>
        <li>Learn a few polite phrases — a little Japanese goes a long way.</li>
        <li>Book popular temples or experiences in advance when possible.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Why this blog</h2>
      <p>
        Travel feels better when shared. This space helps me remember the small
        details (what I ate at 11pm after a long train ride) and gives friends
        and family a spot to follow along. If something helpful comes up, I’ll
        also add practical notes so others can reuse them.
      </p>

      <p>
        If you want me to write about a specific place, food, or travel
        question, tell me and I’ll try to include it in a post.
      </p>

      <p>
        Thanks for stopping by — more stories and photos are coming soon. See
        you on the next post! 🇯🇵
      </p>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
